{"key":"processedPost-8752063","value":{"id":8752063,"first":8751244,"last":8752063,"when":1218377958,"utime":"08/10/08 05:19 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Hydrated lime acts all at once when mixed with water and will raise your ph very fast but if your ph starts to drop later on it will not be able to maintain it like calcium carbonate.</blockquote><br />Not quite.<br />Hydrated lime(calcium hydroxide) is made from limestone, heated to very high temperatures.&nbsp; It's water soluble.&nbsp; It will also maintain pH for the life of the casing.&nbsp; Nothing we do in mycology requires a long term buffer, since the average life of a casing layer is less than two months.<br />If it says 'safer than hydrated lime' there's a 90% chance it's dolomite lime, which is not applicable to mycology due to the high Mg content.<br />RR","title":"Re: Pelletized Lime?"}}